{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> πᾰθ-ημα</b>, ατος, τό, <br /> <i>dative</i> <i>plural</i> παθημάτοις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Comica Adespota” 283 (Aetol. _accusative_ to 12th c.AD: Eustathius Episcopus Thessalonicensis 279.42, 1761.36)\">Refs</a>]:—<b>that which befalls one, suffering, misfortune</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 142, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 4.48, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὸ π. τοῦ Χριστοῦ the <b>passion</b> of Christ, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.2Cor.1.5 \">NT</a>]; of good fortune, χαῖρε παθὼν τὸ π. (deification) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.AD: Orphica “Fragmenta” 32f \">Refs 5th c.AD+</a>]: mostly in <i>plural</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 8.136, etc.; παθήμαθ᾽ ἅπαθον 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 361 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἀκούσια π., opposed to ἑκούσια καὶ ἐκ προνοίας ἀδικήματα, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 1.27 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὰ δέ μοι π. μαθήματα γέγονε my <b>sufferings</b> have been my lessons [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare (πάθος 1.2), 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.207, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Thesmophoriazusae” 199, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Symposium” 222b. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>emotion</b> or <b>condition, affection</b>, π. τῆς ψυχῆς εἶναι τὴν σωφροσύνην, οὐ μάθημα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 3.1.17, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 79d \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to ποίημα, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Sph.” 248b; τὸ τῆς ἑτέρας χειρὸς π. 3rd c.AD: Plotinus Philosophus 4.9.2 \">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]; but in early writers mostly in <i>plural</i>, <b>affections, feelings</b>, opposed to ποιήματα, [<a href=